this seems to be triggered by making enough new secure connections concurrently, with something like:

```
            for (int i = 0; i < 300; i++)
            {
                Channel newChan = new Channel("127.0.0.1:50051", TestCredentials.CreateSslCredentials(), options);
                channels.Add(newChan);
                var k = i;

                var thread = new System.Threading.Thread(new System.Threading.ThreadStart(() =>
                {
                    var client = new Greeter.GreeterClient(newChan);
                    var response = client.SayHello(new HelloRequest { Name = "user " + k.ToString() });
                    Console.WriteLine("Hello: " + response.Message);
                }));
                threads.Add(thread);
                thread.Start();
            }
            threads.ForEach((t) => t.Join());
```

on the client, and a secure, Greeter server from the example.

With 300 such threads, I almost always get this error. Fewer threads than that and it will sometimes happen, but more rarely. 

With insecure connections, many more channels can be used without issues (had no issues with 1000, but I start seeing Unavailable errors if it's stepped up too high, but I think this is expected).

@amitwaisel  so this looks like it's a current problem with the retry logic around SSL handshakes.

For your current situation, try setting the "grpc.initial_reconnect_backoff_ms" argument when constructing the client `Channel`.

For example, this fixed the "handeshake failure exceptions" problem with the repro attempts shown above in this issue:

```
var options = new List<ChannelOption>
{
    new ChannelOption(ChannelOptions.SslTargetNameOverride,
        TestCredentials.DefaultHostOverride),
    new ChannelOption("grpc.initial_reconnect_backoff_ms", "100"),
};

Channel channel = new Channel("127.0.0.1:50051", TestCredentials.CreateSslCredentials(), options);
```

Setting the backoff too a longer period might be necessary, probably depending on the load against the server.

It's default value is actually zero as of right now, though this may change - I think raising it at all should fix the immediate issue.

